{{Lunisolar May|qq=}} '''Lunisolar May''' (旧暦五月) is the fifth {{ill|Month (Calendar)|ja|月 (暦)|lt=Month|lt_ja=月|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Month (Calendar)|qq=}} of the year in the {{ill|Japanese Calendar|ja|和暦|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese Calendar|qq=}} (the {{ill|Lunisolar calendar|ja|太陰太陽暦|1=Lunisolar calendar|2=ja|3=太陰太陽暦|comment=note that this is not the Japanese lunisolar calendar it is any lunisolar calendar|4=ru|5=Лунно-солнечный календарь|6=de|7=Lunisolarkalender|8=es|9=Calendario lunisolar|10=fr|11=Calendrier luni-solaire|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Lunisolar calendar|13=User:Immanuelle/Lunisolar calendar|qq=}}’s {{ill|Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|ja|旧暦|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|11=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|qq=}}).
The month that includes the {{ill|Summer Solstice|ja|夏至|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Summer Solstice|qq=}} becomes May. In the {{ill|Gregorian Calendar|1=Gregorian calendar|2=ja|3=グレゴリオ暦|4=fr|5=Calendrier grégorien|6=de|7=Gregorianischer Kalender|8=tl|9=Kalendaryong Gregoryano|10=ru|11=Григорианский календарь|ja|グレゴリオ暦|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gregorian Calendar|13=User:Immanuelle/Gregorian calendar|qq=}} ({{ill|New Calendar|ja|新暦|1=New Calendar (Japan)|lt=New Calendar|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/New Calendar|13=User:Immanuelle/New Calendar (Japan)|qq=}}), it corresponds approximately to late {{ill|May|ja|5月|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/May|qq=}} to early {{ill|July|ja|7月|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/July|qq=}}.
Another name for May is {{nihongo|'''Satsuki'''|さつき|qq=}}. The origin of the name is explained in [[#Etymology of traditional Japanese name]]{{efn|May|ja|5月|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
In the {{ill|Eastern|ja|東洋|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Eastern|qq=}} {{ill|Lunisolar calendar|ja|太陰太陽暦|1=Lunisolar calendar|2=ja|3=太陰太陽暦|comment=note that this is not the Japanese lunisolar calendar it is any lunisolar calendar|4=ru|5=Лунно-солнечный календарь|6=de|7=Lunisolarkalender|8=es|9=Calendario lunisolar|10=fr|11=Calendrier luni-solaire|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Lunisolar calendar|13=User:Immanuelle/Lunisolar calendar|qq=}}, because the number of days in a month, known as {{ill|Large and Small|ja|大小|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Large and Small|qq=}} (with large months having 30 days and small months 29 days), varies each year, there are years in which May ends on the 29th and May 30th does not exist.
==Etymology of traditional Japanese name== {{afc comment|1=content here taken from [[:ja:5月]][[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 00:31, 11 May 2025 (UTC)}} In {{ill|Japan|ja|日本|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japan|qq=}}, the {{ill|May (Lunisolar)|ja|5月 (旧暦)|lt=Lunar May|lt_ja=旧暦5月|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/May (Lunisolar)|qq=}} is called '''Satsuki''' (さつき), and today it is also used as an alternate name for May of the {{ill|Gregorian calendar|ja|新暦|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gregorian calendar|qq=}}. The term “Satsuki” derives from “Sanahetsuki” (早苗月; さなへつき), meaning “month of early rice seedlings,” which was later shortened. Another theory holds that the element “sa” itself carries the meaning of rice planting, making “Satsuki” simply “month of rice planting.” Additionally, the character 皐 originally denotes rice ears offered to the gods.
In works such as the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}}, the characters “五月” were written and read as “Satsuki,” and it was only later that the name began to be written as 皐月. The notation “皐月” originally appears in Chinese classics as an alternate name for the fifth month of the lunisolar calendar. According to the {{ill|Erya|ja|爾雅|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Erya|qq=}}, in {{ill|ancient China|ja|古代中国|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/ancient China|qq=}} the twelve months were each called “陬如寎余皋且相壯玄陽辜涂” (皋 is the original character for 皐).
“Satsuki” is also the name of a flower. Another alternate name is “Ayamezuki” (菖蒲月; あやめづき).
The lunisolar May corresponds to June through July of the {{ill|Gregorian calendar|ja|新暦|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gregorian calendar|qq=}} and marks the season of the {{ill|plum rain|ja|梅雨|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/plum rain|qq=}}. “Samidare” (五月雨) is another name for the plum rain, and “Satsukibare” (五月晴れ) originally refers to the clear intervals between showers.
In the Asahikawa dialect of the {{ill|Hokkaido Ainu language|ja|北海道アイヌ語|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hokkaido Ainu language|qq=}}, May is called “Muntukkachup” (ムントゥッカチュㇷ゚; {{ill|Ainu language|ja|アイヌ語|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ainu language|qq=}}: mun tukka cup), meaning “month of grass growth”<ref>[https://ainugo.nam.go.jp/siror/monthly/201510.html#01 《ことばからみたアイヌ文化と自然２》アイヌ文化における時間使用 高橋 靖以（北海道大学アイヌ・先住民研究センター博士研究員＝特別寄稿） 月刊シロㇿ]</ref>.
The English month name {{lang|en|May}} is said to derive from the goddess Maia ({{lang|la|Maia}}) of fertility in {{ill|Roman mythology|ja|ローマ神話|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Roman mythology|qq=}}. Of the twelve months, it is the only one without an English abbreviation<ref group="note">English month abbreviations are three letters long; May already has three letters.</ref>.
